Ancillary services (e.g., counseling for mental health and substance use disorders, financial support, and assistance with food and housing) might reduce barriers to ART adherence. Colocating these services with outpatient care (e.g., HIV patient-centered medical home model of the Ryan White HIV/AIDS Program)(
 
  8
 ) can encourage engagement and retention in HIV care. In a study of ART adherence among African American and Hispanic/Latino MSM, younger participants reported better adherence when their care location also offered ancillary services to help them address other needs (
 
  3
 ). Making these services more broadly available and easily accessible might remove barriers to ART adherence and improve health outcomes.
